        <title>Vi set color scheme , line numbers and syntax highlighting</title>
        <link>https://manios.org/2013/04/23/vi-set-color-scheme-line-numbers-and-syntax-highlighting/</link>
        <pubDate>Tue, 23 Apr 2013 16:34:21 +0300</pubDate>
        
        <guid>https://manios.org/2013/04/23/vi-set-color-scheme-line-numbers-and-syntax-highlighting/</guid>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Today I wanted to to set the Color Scheme in vi / vim in my Linux. The default configuration looks ugly:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://manios.org/2013/04/23/vi-set-color-scheme-line-numbers-and-syntax-highlighting/vi_colorscheme_default.png&#34;
	width=&#34;654&#34;
	height=&#34;464&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://manios.org/2013/04/23/vi-set-color-scheme-line-numbers-and-syntax-highlighting/vi_colorscheme_default_hu_2a5d51681eb9b971.png 480w, https://manios.org/2013/04/23/vi-set-color-scheme-line-numbers-and-syntax-highlighting/vi_colorscheme_default_hu_b2cd39647ef4cf42.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;Default coloscheme for linux vi editor&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;140&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;338px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I wanted to look like this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://manios.org/2013/04/23/vi-set-color-scheme-line-numbers-and-syntax-highlighting/vi_colorscheme_evening.png&#34;
	width=&#34;654&#34;
	height=&#34;464&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://manios.org/2013/04/23/vi-set-color-scheme-line-numbers-and-syntax-highlighting/vi_colorscheme_evening_hu_b8b4610a80cbb50c.png 480w, https://manios.org/2013/04/23/vi-set-color-scheme-line-numbers-and-syntax-highlighting/vi_colorscheme_evening_hu_569a2e3590458f.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;Evening colorcheme for linux vi editor&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;140&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;338px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So after some searching in the web I found an article in &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;http://talkbinary.com/linux/how-to-set-the-color-scheme-in-vim/&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;talkbinary&lt;/a&gt; and I did the following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Create in your home directory a file called .exrc
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;touch ~/.exrc
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Open this file and insert the following parameters:
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;2
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;3
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;nb&#34;&gt;set&lt;/span&gt; number
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;syntax on
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;colorscheme evening
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Save the file and you are done! Now you have a nice colourfull VI editor&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
</description>
        </item>
        <item>
        <title>Copy/Paste source code from Eclipse to Microsoft Word</title>
        <link>https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/</link>
        <pubDate>Thu, 08 Mar 2012 09:53:02 +0200</pubDate>
        
        <guid>https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/</guid>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Today I wanted to copy and paste a piece of code from Eclipse Indigo to Microsoft Word 2007 &lt;strong&gt;and keep the syntax highlighting&lt;/strong&gt;. In some cases it worked but in some other not.
After searching in the webI found that if the area you want to copy has folded code in it, the syntax highlight will not be preserved (picture 1)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/codefoldeclipse.png&#34;
	width=&#34;408&#34;
	height=&#34;111&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/codefoldeclipse_hu_988f79f48cdd0dfb.png 480w, https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/codefoldeclipse_hu_626b16e8117820cb.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;code fold&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;367&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;882px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So before you start copying and pasting from Eclipse to Microsoft Word unfold any part of the code you want to copy (picture 2)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/nofolding.png&#34;
	width=&#34;409&#34;
	height=&#34;254&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/nofolding_hu_ce378b5de8a9250d.png 480w, https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/nofolding_hu_de8266b1bc24958e.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;unfold Code in Eclipse&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;161&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;386px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
